The '''electricity sector in Brunei''' ranges from [[Electricity generation|generation]], [[Electric power transmission|transmission]], [[Electric power distribution|distribution]] and [[Electricity market|sales]] of electricity in [[Brunei]].
==Regulator== Electricity sector in Brunei is regulated by the [[Department of Electrical Services]] ('''DES'''; {{lang-ms|Jabatan Perkhidmatan Elektrik}}) under the Ministry of Energy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.des.gov.bn/ |title=Department of Electrical Services, Brunei Darussalam |publisher=Des.gov.bn |date= |accessdate=2014-04-21}}</ref>
==Generation== In 2010, electricity generation in Brunei reached 3,862,000,000 kWh, in which 99% of it was generated from natural gas sources and the remaining 1% was from oil sources.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mecometer.com/infographic/brunei/electricity-sector-statistics/ |title=Brunei : Electricity Sector Statistics |publisher=Mecometer.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-21}}</ref>
===Power stations=== * [[Belingus Power Station]] * [[Berakas Power Station]] * [[Bukit Panggal Power Station]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Dewi Mohd Sofri&lt;br /&gt;TUTONG&lt;br /&gt; |url=http://www.bt.com.bn/news-national/2010/01/12/energy-minister-inspects-power-station |title=Energy Minister inspects power station &#124; The Brunei Times |publisher=Bt.com.bn |date=2010-01-12 |accessdate=2014-04-21}}</ref> * [[Gadong Power Station]] * [[Jerudong Power Station]] * [[Lumut Power Station]] * [[Seria Power Station]]
==Transmission== * 66 kV transmission lines from [[Seria]] to [[Bandar Seri Begawan]]
