[[File:NASA molniya oblique.png|thumb|upright|[[Molniya orbit]] for the Northern hemisphere]]
{{about|a variation of elliptic orbit|geocentric orbit|High Earth orbit}}

A '''highly elliptical orbit''' ('''HEO''') is an [[elliptic orbit]] with high [[orbital eccentricity|eccentricity]], usually referring to [[geocentric orbit|one around Earth]].
Examples of inclined HEO orbits include [[Molniya orbit]]s, named after the [[Molniya (satellite)|Molniya]] Soviet communication satellites which used them, and [[tundra orbit]]s.

Such extremely elongated orbits have the advantage of long dwell times at a point in the sky during the approach to, and descent from, [[apsis|apogee]]. Bodies moving through the long apogee dwell appear to move slowly, and remain at high [[altitude (astronomy)|altitude]] over high-latitude ground sites for long periods of time. This makes these elliptical orbits useful for [[communications satellite]]s. [[Geostationary orbit]]s cannot serve high latitudes due to their altitude from ground sites being too low.<ref name="fortescue"/>

[[Sirius Satellite Radio]] used inclined HEO orbits, specifically the Tundra orbits, to keep two satellites positioned above [[North America]] while another satellite quickly sweeps through the southern part of its 24-hour orbit. The [[longitude]] above which the satellites dwell at apogee in the small loop remains relatively constant as [[Earth's rotation|Earth rotates]]. The three separate orbits are spaced equally around the Earth, but share a common [[ground track]].<ref name="castor-tundra"/>

